{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = {{PAGENAME}} | synonyms = | image = | width = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Collagen-induced arthritis''' (CIA) is a condition induced in mice (or rats) to study [[rheumatoid arthritis]].<ref name=Williams2004>{{cite journal| pmid=15064442 | doi=10.1385/1-59259-771-8:207 | volume=98 | title=Collagen-induced arthritis as a model for rheumatoid arthritis | year=2004 | journal=Methods Mol Med | pages=207–16 | last1 = Williams | first1 = RO}}</ref>
CIA is induced in mice by injecting them with an emulsion of [[complete Freund's adjuvant]] and [[type II collagen]].<ref name=Brand2007>{{cite journal| pmid=17546023 | doi=10.1038/nprot.2007.173 | volume=2 | title=Collagen-induced arthritis | year=2007 | journal=Nat Protoc | pages=1269–75 | last1 = Brand | first1 = DD | last2 = Latham | first2 = KA | last3 = Rosloniec | first3 = EF}}</ref>
In rats, only one injection is needed, but mice are normally injected twice.<ref name=kato1996>[http://ard.bmj.com/content/55/8/535.full.pdf Arthritis in mice induced by a single immunisation with collagen ]</ref>
