A '''narrative verdict''' is a verdict available to [[coroner]]s in [[English law|England and Wales]] and in [[Law of the Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] following an [[inquest]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Leogue |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/inquest-hears-man-84-drove-in-wrong-direction-on-motorway-before-fatal-collision-in-2016-825744.html|title=Inquest hears man, 84, drove in wrong direction on motorway before fatal collision in 2016|date=31 January 2018|newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]] }}</ref> In such a verdict the circumstances of a death are recorded<ref name="bbcservicemandeath">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bradford/6190337.stm |title=Kit delays led to soldier's death |publisher=[[BBC News]] | accessdate=2008-04-01 | date=18 December 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hse.gov.uk/enforce/enforcementguide/wrdeaths/chronology.htm|title=Chronology of proceedings - Work Related Deaths and Inquests - Enforcement Guide (England & Wales) |publisher=[[Health and Safety Executive]] }}</ref> with a brief free-form conclusion either instead of or in addition to one of the standard (and familiar) Short-Form Conclusions. Narrative verdicts were introduced in 2004.<ref> {{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/3351432/Mistakes-missed-chances-and-a-young-life-lost.html |title=Mistakes, missed chances and a young life lost |author=Grice, Elizabeth |date=1 October 2009 |accessdate=1 October 2009 |publisher=[[Daily Telegraph]] | location=London}}</ref>
==Historical examples== The inquest into the [[death of Charlotte Shaw]] concluded with a narrative verdict in October 2010. Charlotte Shaw drowned while crossing a swollen stream on [[Dartmoor]] during training for [[Ten Tors]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/8086383/Coroner-calls-for-safety-improvements-at-Ten-Tors-inquest.html|title=Coroner calls for safety improvements at Ten Tors inquest|last=Savill|first=Richard|date=26 October 2010|newspaper=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>
A coroner delivered a narrative verdict into the death of [[Secret Intelligence Service]] officer [[Death of Gareth Williams|Gareth Williams]] whose decaying corpse was found padlocked into a red sports bag in the bath at his home in August 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17922388|title=MI6 death: Gareth Williams 'probably' killed unlawfully|publisher=BBC News |date=2 May 2012|accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>
